<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>
<task id="001" project="jps-server-rollout">
  <metadata>
    <title>Implement ScopeResolverService.ResolveScopesAsync()</title>
    <phase>1</phase>
    <tags>bff-api, api</tags>
    <estimate>3h</estimate>
    <dependencies>none</dependencies>
    <parallel-group>none</parallel-group>
  </metadata>

  <prompt>
    <goal>Complete the ScopeResolverService.ResolveScopesAsync() method by replacing the empty array stub with parallel Dataverse queries to resolve skill IDs, knowledge IDs, and tool IDs into populated scope objects.</goal>
    <context>
      The JPS (JSON Prompt Schema) server rollout requires scope resolution capabilities to look up referenced skills, knowledge documents, and tools from Dataverse.
      The ScopeResolverService has a stub method (lines 93-106 in ScopeResolverService.cs) that currently returns empty arrays.
      The pattern for parallel resolution already exists in the same file in the ResolvePlaybookScopesAsync() method, which uses GetSkillAsync(), GetKnowledgeAsync(), and GetToolAsync() via Task.WhenAll for parallel execution.
      This task implements the same pattern for ResolveScopesAsync().
    </context>
    <constraints>
      - Follow ADR-010 (DI minimalism) — no new service registrations, reuse existing dependencies
      - Follow ADR-013 (AI Architecture) — scopes are part of the AI tool execution context
      - Follow ADR-014 (AI caching) — use Redis caching for scope lookups where applicable
      - Handle null/missing Dataverse records gracefully (return empty if record not found)
      - Use Task.WhenAll for parallel query execution (match ResolvePlaybookScopesAsync pattern)
      - Maintain performance: scope resolution should not block tool execution
    </constraints>
  </prompt>

  <knowledge>
    <files>
      <file>.claude/adr/ADR-010-di-minimalism.md</file>
      <file>.claude/adr/ADR-013-ai-architecture.md</file>
      <file>.claude/adr/ADR-014-ai-caching.md</file>
      <file>.claude/constraints/ai.md</file>
      <file>.claude/constraints/api.md</file>
      <file>.claude/patterns/ai/analysis-scopes.md</file>
      <file>docs/guides/SPAARKE-AI-ARCHITECTURE.md</file>
      <file>projects/jps-server-rollout/spec.md</file>
    </files>
  </knowledge>

  <steps>
    <step order="1">Read ScopeResolverService.cs lines 93-106 to understand the current ResolveScopesAsync stub and its signature</step>
    <step order="2">Read the ResolvePlaybookScopesAsync() method (same file) to understand the parallel resolution pattern using GetSkillAsync, GetKnowledgeAsync, and GetToolAsync</step>
    <step order="3">Read the ResolvedScopes record structure to understand the return type and field names for skills, knowledge, and tools</step>
    <step order="4">Implement ResolveScopesAsync() following the pattern:
      - Accept AnalysisScopes parameter (containing skillIds, knowledgeIds, toolIds arrays)
      - Create tasks for each resolution using Task.WhenAll:
        - For each skillId in scopes.SkillIds: call GetSkillAsync(skillId)
        - For each knowledgeId in scopes.KnowledgeIds: call GetKnowledgeAsync(knowledgeId)
        - For each toolId in scopes.ToolIds: call GetToolAsync(toolId)
      - Collect results into Lists and return new ResolvedScopes(skills, knowledge, tools)
      - Handle null/empty input gracefully
    </step>
    <step order="5">Verify error handling for missing Dataverse records (null checks, empty list fallback)</step>
    <step order="6">Build the project: `dotnet build src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/`</step>
    <step order="7">Run existing unit tests to ensure no regressions: `dotnet test src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api.Tests/`</step>
  </steps>

  <tools>
    <tool>Read</tool>
    <tool>Edit</tool>
    <tool>Bash(dotnet build)</tool>
    <tool>Bash(dotnet test)</tool>
  </tools>

  <outputs>
    <output>src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Services/Ai/ScopeResolverService.cs</output>
  </outputs>

  <acceptance-criteria>
    <criterion>ResolveScopesAsync() queries Dataverse for all provided skill IDs, knowledge IDs, and tool IDs</criterion>
    <criterion>Parallel execution via Task.WhenAll (matches ResolvePlaybookScopesAsync pattern)</criterion>
    <criterion>Returns populated ResolvedScopes with skills, knowledge, and tools lists</criterion>
    <criterion>Handles null/missing records gracefully (returns empty lists, no exceptions)</criterion>
    <criterion>Project builds successfully</criterion>
    <criterion>Existing tests pass (no regressions)</criterion>
  </acceptance-criteria>
</task>
